[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m **Audit and reversibility are baked in, not added later.** Every merge stores the full provenance. Every unmerge is recorded as a reversible action. The audit log is queryable, immutable, and retained per the institution's records-retention policy (which for clinical records is typically several years to decades, depending on jurisdiction).
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 251     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring is part of the system, not an afterthought.** Compute and report match rate, false-positive rate, and review queue depth by demographic cohort (race, ethnicity, language, age band, geographic region, primary-language). Significant disparities (worse match rate for Hispanic patients than non-Hispanic, for example) are signals that the comparators or the m/u probabilities are not generalizing across populations and need cohort-specific tuning. 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort-stratified accuracy monitoring is part of the system, not an afterthought.** Compute and report match rate, false-positive rate, and review queue depth by demographic cohort (race, ethnicity, language, age band, geographic region, primary-language). Significant disparities (worse match rate for Hispanic patients than non-Hispanic, for example) are signals that the comparators or the m/u probabilities are not generalizing across populations and need cohort-specific tuning. Define explicit disparity alert thresholds: per-cohort recall ratio (worst vs. best cohort), auto-match precision ratio, post-merge unmerge rate ratio, and review-queue depth-per-FTE ratio. Example: `MATCH_RATE_DISPARITY_THRESHOLD = 0.10` fires an alert when the worst-performing cohort's recall falls below 90% of the best-performing cohort's recall. Per-axis threshold overrides are governed by an equity-review committee. When a cohort's sample size drops below a minimum (typically 50 pairs in the gold set), chronic suppression of that cohort's metrics is itself a fairness signal indicating the gold set needs augmentation for that population. The documented diagnose-and-address workflow fires when any alert crosses threshold: identify the contributing comparator or blocking pass, propose cohort-specific tuning, validate on the cohort-stratified gold set, and promote only after committee approval.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m When emitting cohort-dimension metrics to the operational dashboard, use bucketed non-reversible cohort labels (e.g., cohort A, B, C, D, E, unknown) rather than raw demographic attributes. The cohort-label-to-attribute mapping lives in a separate access-controlled store loaded only at dashboard-render time. This prevents demographic inference from the metric stream itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No-link flags protect safety-sensitive populations.** Certain patient records must never be auto-linked, regardless of how high they score. Populations requiring link protection include: patients in state Address Confidentiality Programs (Safe at Home), federal Witness Security participants, sealed adoption records, patients who have requested record separation (gender transition, protected name change), records segmented under 42 CFR Part 2 (substance use disorder, behavioral health), and explicitly-flagged family relationships (twins, parent-infant pairs sharing demographics). The pipeline consults a `no_link_flags` table at three stages: candidate generation (filter flagged records from standard blocking passes), threshold routing (bypass auto-match for any pair containing a flagged record), and review-queue assignment (route flagged-record pairs to a restricted queue staffed only by privacy-office and HIM-leadership roles). Flags are write-protected to privacy-office roles with separate-key encryption. This architectural primitive carries forward to recipes 5.5, 5.7, 5.9, and any cross-organizational matching scenario.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family-aware blocking prevents twin and parent-infant false merges.** Twins share birthday, last name, address, and sometimes first-name initial. The standard blocking passes will produce candidate pairs for twins in almost every pass; the standard comparators will score them high on the shared fields. Without a family-aware guard, these pairs regularly auto-merge. The mitigation: consult the `no_link_flags` table for `family_relationship_explicit` entries and skip comparison of explicitly-flagged family pairs. For pairs that enter scoring through other paths, down-weight comparator scores on shared-family fields (address, phone, insurance) when other fields suggest different individuals.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  253, 259[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  254, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
